In our FigureQA experiments, we follow the overall architecture used by Santoro et al. (2017) in their experiments on CLEVR from pixels, adding one convolutional layer to account for the higher resolution of our input images and increasing the number of channels. We also don't use random rotations for data augmentation, to avoid distortions that might change the correct response to a question.

The object representations are provided by a CNN with the same architecture as the one in the
previous baseline, only dropping the fully-connected layer at the end. Each pixel of the CNN output (64 feature maps of size 8 × 8) corresponds to one "object" oi,·  R64, i  [1, . . . , H · W ], where H and W , denote the height and width, respectively. To also encode the location of objects inside
